inance, social science, art, and the humanities to create a new way of understanding derivative finance that does justice to its social and cultural dimensions. They offer a two-pronged analysis. First, they develop a social understanding of the derivative that casts it in the light of anthropological concepts such as the gift, ritual, play, dividuality, and performativity. Second, they develop a derivative understanding of the social, using financial concepts such as risk, hedging, optionality, and arbitrage to uncover new dimensions of contemporary social reality. In doing so, they construct a necessary, renewed vision of derivative finance as a deeply embedded aspect not just of our economics but our culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aDerivative securitiesxSocial aspects. 0aDerivative securities. 0aMarketsxMathematical models. 0aMarketsxPhilosophy. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / General.2bisacsh  aarbitrage.  acirculation.  aderivative.  agift.  aliquidity.  areplication.  arisk.  aritual.  auncertainty.  avolatility.1 aAppadurai, Arjun, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAyache, Elie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDerman, Emanuel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLee, Benjamin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLee, Benjamin, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLiPuma, Edward, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMartin, Randy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMartin, Randy, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMeister, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWosnitzer, Robert, econtributor.4c